<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_CondVarLock_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_CondVarLock_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    int                                status;
    OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t *impl;

    impl = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_condvar_table, *token);

    status = pthread_mutex_lock(&impl->mut);
    if (status != 0)
    {
        return OS_ERROR;
    }

    return OS_SUCCESS;
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: I examined the entire provided function. There are no calls to memcmp, strcmp, strncmp or any other C standard-library string comparison functions. The code only uses pthread_mutex_lock, an OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET macro to index the implementation table, and simple pointer/assignment and return operations. None of these operations perform or imply comparison of null-terminated strings. Therefore there are no fragments in this function that need investigation for MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14. (If OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET is a macro that expands outside this snippet, its expansion would need separate review, but the shown code contains no memcmp usage.)
